The §f§2Sieve§f is the main source of resources in this pack, but don't worry, it can be automated as soon as you get into the steam age!

§2§fRight-Click the §2Sieve§f with an §2Mesh§f to put it in and then hold Right-Click with the block you want to sift, for example§2 Dirt§f to get the resources you want from this block.

§2Sieves§f can be put nearby each other to sift multiple blocks at once! Pretty neat, or?
Like in almost any other modpacks, you will begin with punching trees to get wood, except this time in the sky and with no exploration needed.

As mentioned in the welcome quest, this modpack features §2Effortless Building§f!

§2Effortless Building§f makes building by a thousand times easier by allowing to build simple structures like floors and walls in an limited range that can be upgraded with §2Range Upgrades§f which you can acquire while progressing.

To access the menu of the mod, press and hold §2ALT§f.

This modpack also features an mod called §2Twerk-Sim 2K16§f!

This mod allows you to grow an sapling without bonemeal by spamming crouch near it.

This Modpack features §2OreExcavation§f!

§2OreExcavation§f allows to mine all blocks of the same type §2at once§f when holding down the button assigned to it (standard assigned to §8§2grave§f, can be changed in controls).

Useful, or?

Breaking §2§2Leaves§f with an §2Crook §fwill increase the overall chance of their drops and allows to obtain an special item called §f§2Silkworm§f.

§2§fRight-Clicking §f§2Leaves§f with an §1§2Silkworm§f will turn them into §2Infested Leaves§f, wait till their "infestation" is done and break them with an §2Crook§f to obtain lots of §2String§f!

Getting an §2Barrel §fwill allow you getting §2dirt§f by putting compostables in like §2saplings §fwhich can be looked up in JEI.

It also allows various§2 fluid transformations§f for different kinds of materials like §2soul sand§f, just right click the barrel in JEI to see what's possible with it!

Getting an §2Crucible§f out of wood will allow you to obtain early §2Water §fin this pack and right-clicking it with §2Dust§k§f while it's filled with §2Water§f will allow you to obtain early §f§3§3§2Clay§f.

Don't forget to make your 2x2 infinite water source, so you don't have to do this everytime you want water!

Welcome to §2Gregtech: Skybound§f!

§2Gregtech: Skybound§f is an lightweight skyblock modpack focussing mainly around §2Gregtech CE: Unofficial§f with some QoL and utility mods like §2Applied Energistics 2§f or §2Effortless building§f!

These Quests here will try to teach you through the early progression of this modpack and of Gregtech.

Hope you enjoy this pack!
The §2Hammer§f allows you to grind down various blocks, like §2Cobblestone§f into §3§2Gravel§f, §2Gravel§f into §2Sand§f, and so on.
It's finally time to craft an §2Furnace§f! No funny description this time.

The §2Clay Bucket§f is the earliest way of transferring Fluids like §2Water§f.
Note that it will break when transferring §2Lava§f!

The §2Crucible§f made out of §2Bricks§f will allow you to obtain §2Lava§f easily by putting any Stones in it when an appropiate heat source like an §2Torch§f is under it. 
Be sure to check JEI which stone yields the most §2Lava§!!

§2Witch Water§e§f is an very useful fluid early and can be used to create as example an endless §2Dirt§f or §2Stone§f generator that generates all types of Stone!

To obtain §2Witch Water§f, use the §2Ancient Spores§f you obtained by sifting §2Dirt§f earlier on an 3x3 §2Dirt§f field by clicking on the middle block to transform it to §2Mycelium§f. Place an §2Barrel §fwith §2Water§a§f in it and it will begin slowly to transform into §2Witch Water§f! Note that this process also generates§2 Mushrooms§f.

As mentioned in an earlier quest, §2Witch Water§f allows you to make an unlimited §2Stone§f generator that generates any type of Stone! 

Just like in an normal Cobblestone generator, let the §2Lava§f flow to the §2Witchwater§f to create Stones. 

Different stream lengths of the §2Witch Water§f will create different §3§2Stones§f as followed:

1 Block - §2Diorite
§f2-3 Blocks - §2Granite
§f4-7 Blocks - §2Andesite

As mentioned in the earlier quest, you can make with§2 Witch Water§f an generator that generates endless §2Dirt§f. You can do that by making an simple Cobblestone generator but instead of §2Lava§f you use §2Witch water§f! §k§k§k

Flint Tools are the first GT Tools available in this pack and have fairly decent durability.

Some Tools have an unique feature compared to their vanilla versions, for example will the §2Axe§f cut down a whole tree instead of needing to break every single log, or the §2Pickaxe§f will place §2Torches§f when Right-Clicking a block.

Now that you have obtained all kinds of Stones, it's time to actually obtain some important resources like §f§2Iron§k§f or §2Copper§f!

Here won't be listed where to obtain which resource, so please look up in JEI where to obtain which ore!

Gregtech also has Tools that are mainly used for Crafting like the §a§3§2Hammer §for §2File§e.

§fThose will be used ALOT in the progression, but don't worry, you can later on make items like §2Plates §fand §2Screws §fin machines so you don't have to make it by hand all the time.

NOTE: This quest accepts either§2 Wrought Iron§f or §2Iron §ftools.
Finally, an real Bucket.

§2Wrought Iron§f is an very durable tool material early on, it has the double durability of §2Iron§f and is very easy to make.

§k§l§fIt's made by putting§2 Iron Nuggets§f in an §2Furnace§  and combining the §foutcoming §2Wrought Iron Nuggets§f into an §2Wrought Iron Ingot§f.

§2Bronze§f is an important alloy made out of §2Tin§f and§2 Copper§f that will be needed to get into the§e Steam Age§f!

It is made by combining §2§f3 §2Copper dust§f and 1 §2§2Tin dust§f in an crafting table and smelting the outcoming §2Bronze dust §fin an §2Furnace§f.

The §2Bronze Mesh§f is the next tier Mesh, allowing to obtain new materials like §2Redstone§f or §2Silver§f. 

These materials will be important in the later progression.

The §2Block Breaker§f will automatically break blocks in front of it. It can be used to easily automate the generators you already built up.

It's working state can be easily toggled with an lever.

As you may have noticed, §2Charcoal§f cannot be made in an §2Furnace§f, you need to make it in an §2Coke Oven§f.

The §2Coke Oven§f§f is the first Multiblock you can make in this Pack, it's 3x3x3 and hollow in the middle.

It's the early way of obtaining §2Charcoal§f and gives as byproduct§2 Creosote§f, which can be used to make §2Treated Wood§f that will become handy later on.

The §2Hatches§f allow for basic automation with hoppers, pipes, etc. They can output both §2Creosote §fand §2Charcoal§f and allow inputting §2Wood§f.

It also accepts §2Coal§f, and will output an more powerful fuel called §2Coke§f!

Getting an §2Solid Fuel Steam Boiler§f will bring you torwards §eAge 0 - The Steam Age§f!

Simply just put §2Water§f into the §2Boiler§f and then put an burnable fuel in like §2Coal§f§f and wait for it to build up heat by watching the red bar going up, then it will begin to produce §2Steam§f! It won't output §2Steam§f to the bottom, it's the best to use that side to input §2Water§f from that side (It was specifically implemented for this).

§fNOTE: Never put §2Water§f into the §2Boiler§f while it's hot and empty, else it will explode!

Welcome to §eAge 0 - The Steam Age§f! While you don't have electricity yet, you can make Steam Machines now, which will help you out alot early.

Hint: You can turn off Machines - both Electric and Steam ones - with an §2Soft Mallet§f, so if your Steam Machine ran out of §2Steam§f, be sure to turn it off and turn it back on as soon as the §2Boiler §fmade more!

The §2Primitive Pump§f is an Multiblock that produces water infinitely, but is limited in how much it produces per second.

It depends on the Biome on how much it produces, for example building it in an  Ocean/River Biome will make it produce 1000L/s.

NOTE: Compared to the other Multiblocks, this one needs to be built EXACTLY like the Preview in JEI.

In Gregtech, Fluid and Item transportation is done using §3§2Pipes§f.
§3§2Pipes§f are the only way nearby an ME-System to transfer Items and Fluids around in this pack.

§2Pipes§f will not auto-extract Fluids/Items from Blocks, you need to use something that can do that like §2Hoppers §f(There's an version out of wood in this pack), or §2Covers§f (Those will be shown in an later quest).

Each Pipe has different transfer rates, depending on the Material they are made. The bests you can make right now are §2Tin §fand§2 Bronze§f ones.

You can see in their description which can transfer Items and which can transfer Fluids, it also depends on the Material.

NOTE: Output Hatches and Buses from Multiblocks will auto-insert into Pipes, but be sure that the output face is showing where the Pipe is, else it won't auto-insert!
A §2Stone Barrel§a§f is used to obtain things like §2Obsidian§f or §2Netherrack§f, because those require that §L§2Lava §fis in the Barrel and the Wooden one cannot take it.

The §2§2Alloy Smelter§f is the first Steam Machine you should make, as it allows to make all Alloys you will need in this Age and the next. 

It also allows you to make easier §2Bronze§f, because it gives you 4 instead of only 3 and doesn't need dust to alloy it together.
The§2 Steam Macerator§f allows you to easily grind down Items and Blocks with Steam, no more needing a mortar to grind down stuff!

Ore Processing in Gregtech will double the output and if done complete will give some neat byproducts, but with the current machines it's way too slow to do. 
So you should ignore it before§e Age 3§f§,, because the amount of ores you get at this moment will last you for a while without doubling it.

The§2§2§2 Steam Sieve§f can perform sifting recipes, allowing you to easily automate sifting. No more hours of right-clicking!

NOTE: You should get an better infrastructure before trying to do full automation, one boiler will not be enough!

The §2Steam Grinder§f and§2 § §2Steam Oven §fare very powerful multiblocks that §fcan process 8 Items and once, but only take 1.5x of the time it needs normally! 
Time to replace those slow ass Steam Machines!

Note: In quests like this one, only either task need to be done, not both!
§2Potin§f is an very powerful material for §2Fluid Pipes§,, it has the best stats §ffor those in this Age and will be used still alot later too.

The §2Rock Breaker§f allows you to generate pretty fast any type of stone, faster than your current generator! 
But note that it only can generate one type of Stone that you want it to generate.
As the name says, the§2 Steam Compressor§f allows you to compress things with the power of Steam! It is needed to progress further, so you definitely should make it.
The §2Steam Furnace§k§f§f allows you to cook Items with Steam instead of needing to feed it everytime with solid fuels.

The§2 Primitive Blast Furnace§f is one of the main goals in this Age and is an important step getting towards §eAge 1 - Low Voltage§f!

With either some §2Coal§f, §2Coke§f or §2Charcoal§f and §2Iron §for §2Wrought Iron§f§f you will be finally able to get some §2Steel§f!§2 Wrought Iron§f will process faster into§2 Steel§f than normal §2Iron§f.

The§2 Forge Hammer§f allows you to make §2§f2 § Plates with only 3 Ingots and a bit of Steam, saving alot of material early! 
It reflects all Ex Nihilo §2Hammer§f recipes too.

High Pressure Steam Machines are faster versions of the normal Steam Machines and are as fast as Low Voltage Machines! 
These will halve the time it'll need to process things for all Machines, but will consume more steam too!
The next thing you should make are §2Molds§k§k§f. Those are important to progress further and allow you to §fmake §2Glass§f,§2 Rubber §fand §2Vacuum Tubes§f.

The §2Steam Solar Boiler§f allows you to produce §3§2Steam§f with only §2Water§f and Sunlight!

NOTE: The High Pressure variant will produce the double amount of §2Steam §fcompared to the normal one!

The §2Steam Liquid Boiler§f allows you to produce lots of §2Steam§f with either §2Creosote§f or §2Lava§k§f as Fuel.

NOTE: The High Pressure variant will produce the double amount of §2Steam §fcompared to the normal one!

§2Netherrack§f§f§f will allow you to obtain §2Sulfur§f, which is an important ingredient to obtain§2 Rubber§f.

It is obtained by right-clicking an §2Stone Barrel§f§f filled with §2Lava§f with§2 Redstone§f. It can be automated using§2 Item Pipes§f too!
Obtaining §2Rubber§f is an important step towards§2§e Age 1 - Low Voltage§f as it allows you to make cables and is used in alot of other recipes.

§2Covers §fare extremly powerful in what they can do, but for now we will only focus on those for the §2Item and Fluid Pipes§f.

The§2 Robot Arm§f allows you to extract and insert items from any Block that has an inventory, it's speed is determined by the tier you have crafted. You can see on the Tooltip how much it can transfer.

The§3§2 Pump§f is similar to the §1§2Robot Arm§f, just for Fluids instead of Items.

Those should help you alot out in getting decent automation finally!

§2Vacuum Tubes§f are one of the ingredients needed for your first §2LV Circuits§f! 

I'd recommend to batch-craft already components, as you will need lots of §2Circuits§f for Machines and such.
The§2 Resistors§f are the next Circuit part you should craft, be sure to go the §2Fine Copper Wire§f route for crafting, as it will allow you to safe resources!
The §2Basic Circuit Board §fis the last part you need for your first §2LV Circuits§f.

The§2 Steam Extractor§f will be needed to obtain §2Raw Rubber§f, which can be processed down together with§2 Sulfur§9§f into §2Rubber§f.§2 §f
Put some §2Sticky Resin §f it and it should begin to process it, note that it will take some time to process!

§2Sticky Resin§f, when processed is used for making §2Rubber§f which is an important material that you will need lots of by now!

It is obtained by farming§2 Rubber Trees§f. You should've got already an §2Rubber Sapling §ffrom Sifting§2 Dirt§f.

The §2Portable Cell§f is like an Backpack, so you can store in there Items you will need often like §2Tools§f but don't want to clutter your inventory with it everytime.

Note that it uses Energy and will lose some by the time you have it open, but don't worry it won't be long anymore till you can charge it!
It's finally time to make some §2LV Circuits§f! You will need ALOT of them, so it's recommend to already begin to batchcraft them so you don't need to craft them everytime again.
The next thing you will need is a§2 Machine Casing§f. You will need those in any Machine you want to craft and in other parts too like §2Hatches§f and §2Buses§f in Multiblocks.

It's finally time to make an §2Basic Steam Turbine§f and getting into §eAge 1 - Low Voltage Age§f!

The §2Steam Turbine§f will begin to produce Energy§f as soon as you feed it with §2Steam§f, but be sure to make enough §2Boilers§f as you will need ALOT to keep up now.

Time to make some §2LV Electric Motors§f! You will need this component alot as well now, so you should batch-craft them too!

NOTE: You can only make the §2Magnetic Iron Rod§f for now, so be sure to look at the second recipe in JEI.

The §2Steel Mesh §fis the third §a§fMesh you can obtain and allows you to obtain rarer Materials like §2§2Diamond§f and §2Graphite§e§e§f. 

You will need it in the LV age!

Welcome to §eAge 1 - Low Voltage§f! Now that you have got Electricity and Electric Machines, the real fun of Gregtech will begin!

Alot of things will be hard to understand if you play Gregtech for the first time, but will get alot easier as you begin to understand.

This Quest explains how §3Energy§2§f works in Gregtech.

Like in real life, you have§2 Amperage§f and §2Voltage§f. Each §2§3Tier §fhas an specific amount of §2Voltage§f that it can handle maximum. For example, §e§2§2§3§eULV §2§fhas an §2Voltage§f of 16 §3EU {Energy Units§f§3}§f§f per tick, so it§f can handle all recipes that take up to 16 §3Energy Units§f per tick. Anything above is §2§eLV§f, which can handle up to 32 §3Energy Units §fper tick and so on.
Each §2Cable§f also has an §3§2Voltage §floss per Block! Be sure to watch out for that!

§2Amperage§f§2 {Amps} §ftakes the §3Energy Units§f§f xN, where N is the number of §2Amps§f. Each §2§3Tier §fhas x4 §3§3§2Amps§f of the lower §4§3Tier§f, so you can power as example an §2§3§eMV §fMachine with an §2Cable§f with §2§eLV §fpower that has x4 §2Amps§f or more.

NOTE: While you can power an §2§eLV §fMachine with an §2§eLV§f §2Cable§f that has §2Amps§f higher than 1, but you can't power it with an §eMV §f§2Cable§f, it will EXPLODE! This has the reason that the §2Cable§f of the corresponding §3Tier§f will only output as much §3§2Voltage§f as the Machine needs.

Gregtech has it's Machines divided in §3Tiers§f. Each Recipe in an Machine has an minimum §2§3Tier §fneeded to be able to be processed. 

There are 10 Tiers in Gregtech by standard:
§e0 - Ultra Low Voltage (ULV)
1 - Low Voltage (LV)
2 - Medium Voltage (MV)
3 - High Voltage (HV)
4 - Extreme Voltage (EV)
5 - Insane Voltage (IV)
6 - Ludicrious Voltage (LuV)
7 - Zero Point Module (ZPM)
8 - Ultimate Voltage (UV)
9 - Ultra High Voltage (UHV)

§eULV§f doesn't have any Machines.

§2§2§fYou may notice that §2§eSteam §fis not listed here, that has the reason that it is not directly an §3Tier§f on it's own and can perform all recipes that are §3§eLV§f.

§fUsing an higher §2§3§3Tier§f to process an Recipe with an lower §3Tier§f needed, the time of the Recipe gets halfed each time by how much the current §3Tier §fis greater than the §3Tier§f needed, so an §2§3§§§eLow Voltage§f Recipe in an §f§3§d§e§eHigh Voltage§f Machine have the time cut in half two times.

§aBatteries§r for storing energy! They can be put into the energy slot at the bottom middle of machine GUIs, or in a §3Battery Buffer§r.

Batteries in your inventory can be shift right-clicked to enable §dcharging§r your EU items.

§7LV§r, §bMV§r, and §6HV§r Batteries come in three forms, allowing you to pick the one you find the best depending on materials you have. §dLithium§r has the best capacity, followed by §dCadmium§r, then §dSodium§r.

My recommendation is: find a Salt vein, and either §aelectrolyze Salt§r for §dSodium§r, or §aOre wash crushed Lepidolite§r for §dLithium§r.


Get §eany§r Battery to complete this quest.

Prepare §a128 Cupronickel§r, §a32 Bronze§r and §a16 Tin Alloy§r to craft the Heating Coils for your Electric Blast Furnace.

This is still less than half of the cost of the entire EBF in raw materials. You will also need about a stack each of Invar and Steel.

Note that §aCupronickel§r can be made in the §9Alloy Smelter§r. It's much faster than mixing!


The Cupronickel Coils will allow the EBF to perform recipes up to §d1,800K§r (ignoring Voltage bonuses). That's pretty hot if you ask me.

§oMV Circuits! Does this mean MV Age...? Well, do you have Aluminium?§r

Each Electric Age has Circuits corresponding to its tier. The Good Electronic Circuit is the §dfirst MV Circuit§r you can make, out of three.

The next thing you should probably do is craft a §3Circuit Assembling Machine§r to make more Circuits! For cheaper!


§6Having this and Aluminium will grant access to MV Machines.§r

§aAluminium§r is the main ingredient for §bMV§r machine hulls. Check aaaall the way to the other side for §2Sapphire Quest§r if you haven't acquired §aAluminium Dust§r yet.

Once you setup an §3MV Electrolyzer§r, you can get §aAluminium§r through many other ores. All of this quest's rewards bear §aAluminium§r.

The process of smelting Aluminium can be accelerated with §9Nitrogen§r, which is obtained by centrifuging §9Air§r from a §3Gas Collector§r.


§6You will still need MV Circuits in order to make MV machines.§r

§oSteel can form a lot of Alloys... such as Blue Steel, Red Steel, Black Steel... Fun names?§r


Vanadiumsteel is required in small quantities in progression. It is §6nearly four times as durable§r as Steel for GregTech tools. The Vanadium comes from §aVanadium Magnetite§r, which you have probably encountered in Magnetite veins.


Take some Blue Steel free of charge, that one is twice as durable as Steel.

You have unlocked a new Tier of Circuits!
The Integrated Logic Circuit is an alternate §7LV §aCircuit§r, which can be upgraded to §bMV§r, and then §6HV§r.


§9Note:§r This is not a strict upgrade to the cost of Circuits, you would need to get to the next Tier for that, just slightly further down in the MV Age. Why would you need this Circuit type then? You need it to get to §6HV circuits§r.


§bLore:§r The circuit progression in GTCEu is mostly based on GT5u's progression. However it has been rebalanced to not be as painful, specifically this circuit tier which was a complete bait!
The MV Circuit for the Integrated Tier.

§oAlright, technically HV Circuit and Stainless Steel means you can move to HV... but let's not rush things.§r

The first thing you should probably make with them is a §3MV Circuit Assembler§r, to unlock the new tier of Circuits right away; they are the §dreal payoff§r.

§6The best LV Circuits§r! You will be making these for the remainder of the game.

Eventually (in EV Age), they will become even cheaper.

§6The best MV Circuits§r! You will be making these for the remainder of the game.

Eventually (in IV Age), they will become even cheaper.

Better HV Circuits, much §6cheaper§r and easier to make than from the previous Tier.


§6You should now be ready to move on the HV Chapter§r, unless you still need to scale up Power Production.

Your first EV Circuit gets a unique texture.

It will be needed during the HV Age.

Stainless Steel is pretty much any Steel you may encounter in everyday's life. It is extremely resilient against corrosion.§r§r

Stainless Steel is the material for §6HV§r components, like Aluminium for §bMV§r and Steel for §7LV§r. It is also used in high quantities for the §3Distillation Tower§r. It unlocks a lot of §6nice stuff§r as well!

It requires §cChrome§r, obtained mainly from §cRuby§r, and §2Manganese§r, obtained from §2Pyrolusite§r and others in its vein.

Smelting Stainless Steel requires §dHV Power§r, which I highly doubt you have at this point. Scaling Power Production is crucial!

What I would §9recommend§r would be to get a second EBF going. They can share blocks, so that is only §a10 Cupronickel Coils§r instead of 16.
Have one EBF run off MV, for Aluminium and any other recipes requiring MV Power, and one running off HV with §32 MV Energy Hatches§r.

§oIs it getting hot in here?§r

§3Kanthal Heating Coils§r are the next major step in progression. This increases the temperature of your §3Blast Furnace§r to §d2,700K§r, allowing you to process new materials. They may also §eaccelerate§r less hot recipes - check the next quest for details.

You will need §a128 Ingots§r, which will take easily over an hour. You can move on to other projects while your §3EBF§r is hard at work.

An §3MV Chemical Bath§r is required to cool §cHot Ingots§r down. They're §chot§r when held, as the name implies. §oMaybe you should save your hands and automate this...§r

With the construction of a §3Kanthal EBF§r, you're now able to make §dSilicon Ingots§r!

The first §1IV§r circuit. Congratulations on making it this far!

This will be used in the §5EV§r tier.

§bLore:§r The texture for the Mainframes is taken from an image of an IBM zEnterprise mainframe. https://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2010/07/22/roundup-ibms-new-zenterprise-mainframe

§oTrying to match the heat of the Sun huh? But still a long way to go.§r

§3Nichrome Heating Coils§r increase the temperature of your §3Blast Furnace§r to §d3,600K§r.

Despite not being required §oyet§r, it still is a good idea to upgrade your primary §3EBF§r for the sweet §6Coil bonuses§r.


§bLore:§r In original GregTech 5, there were only three types of coils. This was the last tier.

§oTitanium has the highest corrosion resistance and strength-to-density ratio of any metallic element.§r

§aTitanium§r is the main material for §5EV§r machines. Be sure you build your closed loop for Rutile and prepare to run a dedicated §3EBF§r for hours.

It also is the first material requiring an §6HV§r §9Vacuum Freezer§r to cool. You won't need to upgrade your freezer's power inputs as often as your EBF, but power requirements will still slowly go up, so keep that in mind.

The §5EV§r Age is the end for single block generators! You will need to run several §3HV Generators§r! And later upgrade to Multiblock Generators.
While Multiblock generators are much more expensive, they have the ability to be much more energy efficient!

How to get Platinum:
§9-§r From §aNickel Ore§r byproduct, either §3Chemical Bath§r of §3HV Macerator§r (be sure to remember to check the ore byproduct JEI page!)
§9-§r From §aSheldonite vein§r in the End
§9-§r From §aPlatinum Group Sludge§r, a complicated chain granting all Platinum Group metals. Highly §cunrecommended until IV Age§r, but eventually required, as with many chains.


Platinum is needed in small amounts for §dSMD Diodes§r, and for diverse recipes starting in the §5EV§r Age.


§bLore:§r Mekanism's primary material was planned to be Platinum. However GregoriusT complained about it being such a rare material that would be spread all over the world.

§oBatteries are cool, but you know what's cooler? Science-fiction Batteries!§r

§aEnergium Crystals§r store a significant amount of §9EU§r. They are also arguably cheaper!

The Best Battery-like item, for §5EV§r!

The §aLapotron Crystal§r requires quite a bit of nested crafting, so craft it in bulks or automate it with AE2 patterns.

§bMV§r Batteries will be convenient to buffer Energy, just like it was useful for §7LV§r.

The cost in §aSodium§r or §aLithium§r bumps to 8 dusts, so you may use whatever you have the most of.
The difference in storage is not that huge after all...

Get §eeither§r Battery to complete the Quest.

§o250 Million EU in a Battery, 25Min of Power when drained constantly!? That's amazing!§r

The §aLapotronic Energy Orb§r should be the beginning of the end of your energy storage struggles.
This Energy Storage is perfectly suited if your Power Generation is inconsistent, or if you need to buffer large amounts due to the nature of §3Large Turbines§r.

It does not come quite cheap though. The §dEngraved Lapotron Crystal Chips§r are worth §a8 Lapotron Crystals§r.

The §aPortable Scanner§r, or §aTricorder§r, is GTCEu's debug tool.
It shows you a block's details, the details of the energy network, its current status and contents, and its impact on performance.

Using this anywhere will also display a percentage of fluid remaining in the fluid vein, for the §3Fluid Rigs§r.

§bLore:§r This little useful device comes from GregTech 5. It was extremely useful in the early days, because very little information was given by GUIs or Waila.

§oIf you're still running off Steam, here is a solution for you! But if I wanted to be honest... Steam as a power option really isn't worth it at this point anymore. Stay tuned for when/if we rework it.§r

The §3Large Steam Turbine§r is a multiblock Steam Turbine for §6HV§r power. It is a quite expensive multiblock to generate 1024 EU/t, but it also the ability to scale to §9higher Power Production and higher Effiency§r.

The Turbine will output §dDistilled Water§r given an §3Output Hatch§r, so you can loop it back to your §3Large Boilers§r.
Not completely recommend, as your Boilers will end up exploding if the system fails...

Each Large Turbine will require a §aTurbine Rotor§r and a §3Rotor Holder§r. More on the Turbine mechanics in the §lnext§r Quest.

§9Note:§r This Quest §eonly§r requires the Controller, but you still need all the multiblock parts.
Turbines §cvoid§r energy that they can not output. If you plan on using this with HV power, use a Rotor with close to 100% Power stat.

§oThe Large Turbines are the most complex Multiblock Generators there exists in GTCEu in the present day.§r

Let's start with the §4drawbacks§r of §3Large Turbines§r:
§9-§r They work off §eInertia§r, which requires continuous running to achieve maximum Power.
§9-§r Any excess unconsumed Energy produced will be §cvoided§r. You §lwill§r want to use large Energy Buffers, and an §3Advanced Energy Detector§r.
§9-§r They require a §aRotor§r which loses durability over time and eventually §cbreak§r.
§9-§r A little bit of Math is required to get the expected results.


Now, with the §6upsides§r:
§9-§r They can scale §9Power§r production substancially higher than the base output thanks to tiered §3Rotor Holders§r.
§9-§r The §aRotor§r can give a huge boost to §dFuel efficiency§r, and §9Power§r production.
§9-§r Self satisfaction for setting them up properly (yay!).


§3Rotor Holders§r above the tier of the §3Large Turbine§r will §6double§r the production for every tier, multiplicatively.
§3Rotor Holders§r above the tier of the §3Large Turbine§r will increase the efficiency by 10% for every tier, additively.

§aRotors§r have a §9Power§r, §dEfficiency§r and §4Durability§r that are based on tool stats.
§9Power§r multiplies the production of the §3Turbine§r. This stacks multiplicatively with the §3Rotor Holder§r.
§dEfficiency§r reduces the fuel consumption. This stacks multiplicatively with the §3Rotor Holder§r.
§4Durability§r is the lifetime of the §aRotor§r in seconds, when the §3Turbine§r§r is active.


§2§lIn summary:§r

The §9Power§r output affects both the fuel consumption and the EU/t generation. It is calculated with the following formula:
§eproduction = baseEUt * rotorPower * 2^(rotorHolderTier - turbineTier)§r

The §dEfficiency§r reduces the fuel consumption, but does not alter the EU/t generation. It is calculated with the following formula:
§eefficiency = rotorEfficiency * (1 + 0.1 * (rotorHolderTier - turbineTier))§r


§2§lSome examples:§r

Large Steam Turbine, with Ultimet Rotor and EV Rotor Holder:
Production = 1024 * 1.60 * 2 = 3276 EU/t
Efficiency = 1.30 * 1.10 = 143%
(Steam consumption = 4582 L/t, this is above a Titanium Boiler, or a TungstenSteel Boiler with ~70% throttle)

Large Gas Turbine, with Chrome Rotor and EV Rotor Holder:
Production = 4096 * 1.70 * 1 = 5325 EU/t
Efficiency = 1.55 * 1.00 = 155%
(The same fuel consumption would produce 3435 EU/t using 6.7 Turbo Gas Turbines)

Large Plasma Turbine, with HSS-S Rotor and ZPM Rotor Holder:
Production = 16834 * 2.50 * 4 = 168340 EU/t
Efficiency = 1.80 * 1.20 = 216%
(This is more than a ZPM Amp!)

§bDigital fluid storage§r is pretty cool. Each §b1k ME Fluid Storage Cell§r holds up to §d5 types§r of fluid, and can hold §6over 8,000 buckets§r of those 5 fluid types! That's more than a §3Super Tank 2§r!

Higher tier §aFluid Storage Cells§r hold even more fluid, but are only available quite a bit later.

You may want to §4format§r Fluid Storage Cells to certain types, to prevent the network from clogging. Make a §3Cell Workbench§r to do so.

A completely §doptional§r Multiblock (§oin playtesting, I kept using HV singleblock miners and was content with them§r).

The §3Larger Miner§r is ridiculously good to collect ores from veins!

Ores are mined as if they were §amacerated§r, but they yield §6three times§r as many §dCrushed ores§r.

You will need §aDrilling Fluid§r automation to run this.

You might also want to use a §3Quantum Tunnel§r from AE2 and §3GTEU P2P Tunnels§r to transfer the items and to power it up.


§bLore:§r There were some interesting side effects from porting this over from Gregicality, as the multiblock originated from GregTech 5... It's not perfect, as there isn't really any advantage on upgrading this miner to the advanced versions. We were thinking of rebalancing the energy costs and yield per tier, so there may be rework for this miner at some point!

The ore generation in §2GregTech§r is very different to vanilla or normal modded Minecraft. All ores generate in §6huge veins§r which can contain §dthousands§o§r of ore blocks!

The full extent of ore generation is explained in the Tips and Tricks tab, but here is what you need to know:

§9-§r Ore veins generate in a §4Grid§r. Every vein is §9spaced by 3 chunks§r from one to another in a cardinal direction. We have added §2In Game Info§r to display if you are located in an Ore vein in the top-left corner of your screen, as seen in GregTech: New Horizons.

§9-§r §dSurface Rocks§r indicate a nearby type of vein. Pick one up and check §c§r§5JEI§r (press U) to see the types of ores beneath it.

§9-§r It's a good practice to make §dWaypoints§r (default §4B§r, keybind conflicts with Baubles) to every vein you find, and to label their type. You may want to come back to it several times.

§oLiquids, Gases... It's all the same here.§r

§3Fluid Pipes§r will transport Steam between machines for you.

Each Pipe has a certain §dthroughput§r in L/t (mB/t), and a Temperature Limit (this is only relevant right now for Steam, as it will burn Wooden Pipes). Some pipes have other attributes you don't need to worry about for now.

Each material has several §dsizes§r for Pipes. The bigger the Pipe, the higher the throughput.

For example, a normal Bronze Fluid Pipe transfers 120 L/t. It also has a 1,200 L internal buffer.

§9Reminder:§r 1 second = 20 ticks. Assuming the server does not lag.


Get §eeither§r a Small, or Normal Bronze Fluid Pipe to complete this quest. Both are used in crafting.

§9Note:§r GT6-style Pipes are §denabled§r. It means that placing Pipes connect them only to the block they were placed against. To open more connections, use your §5Wrench§r on the grid.
You can also shift-right click with your §5Wrench§r to disable input from a side. This can help counteract sloshing.

The §9Digital Interface Cover (DIC)§r is a visual Cover. It can show useful things like the status and progress of Machines, or the amount of fluids stored in a Super Tank.

It can be upgraded to a §dWireless §9Digital Interface Cover§r in order to link the Cover and machine to the §3Central Monitor§r.

The full extent of the §9DIC§r's capabilities are listed in the GTCEu Wiki and the §4Terminal§r.

Higher-tier Generators will increase their fuel consumption proportionally to their Generation rate, keeping the duration of fuels and the specific amount of energy from fuels the same. The §3Advanced Steam Turbine§r will use §d5,120 mB Steam§r per second, equivalent to §d256 mB/t§r.

Get §eany§r of the generators to complete this quest, but you may prefer starting off with the §3Advanced Steam Turbine§r.

There are a few new power options available for the §9§bMV§r age. Selecting the Generators and pressing §4U§r will let you see which fuels count as §aCombustion§r or §aGas§r.
Quests in the top left corner of this Chapter are for the valuable Power options.

If you stick to §9Steam§r Power generation, you will probably need a §3Large Boiler§r.

The §9Portable Cell§r can hold items for you! It holds up to §a27§r types of items.

What's more, it acts just like a regular AE2 Storage Cell. Once you get an ME System running, you can simply drop it into an §aME Drive§r or §b§aME IO Port§r for convenience.

The Portable Cell's energy only drains when it's open. With §6167 minutes§r of juice stored in it thanks to changed config, you shouldn't worry about it running out of energy.
Regardless, you will be able to §dcharge§r it in §7LV§r Age in §3machine Charger slots§r, §3Turbo Chargers§r or §3Battery Buffers§r.

In general, it is worth §9bulk-crafting§r more than you need, so you will have the intermediates ready for more crafts.

Since we're part of the §2GregTech: CEu§r community, I will plug some of the §9addons§r here that you can safely add to your instance (running list):

§9How to auto-build:§r With your §4Multiblock Tool§r in hand, shift-right-clock the Mulitblock Controller that you placed in World, and the structure will be built according to the blocks in your inventory.

Note that the Hatches may not always end up being on the positions you wanted, but at least it placed all the other Blocks for you!

§oIV Age is truly the Age of automation, and finally this should be worth to automate all the ores... if you wish, that is.§r

What you will §4§lneed§r to automate §6Ore Processing§r on a large scale:
§9-§r One or few §3IV Macerators§r (or higher tier).
§9-§r A few §3Processing Arrays§r (PA), to place your low tier machines inside, §eor§r use the §2Gregicality Multiblocks§r variants.

§9-§r One or a few MV §3Electrolyzers§r, possibly in a PA.

What you may §eoptionally§r add:
§
§9-§r A few LV §3Ore Washers§r for quick washing purposes.

§9-§r §3Sifters§r of any tier (higher tier = better chanced output), for gem ores.
§9-§r §3Electromagnetic Separators§r.


To answer questions:

§d-§r Why §7LV§r Machines? Overclocking is not energy efficient, which is why it is generally better to go for low tier machines in passive setups. One could also argue they are cheaper.
§3Processing Arrays§r make up for the sheer amount of machines you are making. If you wish, you can still use higher tier machines, but the power draw will be bigger.
If you have §2Gregicality Multiblocks§r, just use those instead.

§d-§r Optional things? Yes. Obtaining most Byproducts or getting better yields are completely up to you.
§3Thermal Centrifuges§r are close to mandatory, as they unlock a §6unique Byproduct§r from the maceration step.

§d-§r What ores should I prioritise? There are crucial ores and Byproducts to not miss out.
Chalcopyrite, Chalcocite, Bornite, Tetrahedrite, Pentlandite and Sheldonite ores should all be turned into §dPurified Crushed§r and sent to the §6Platinum Group Metal§r chain.
Purified Crushed Galena and Sphalerite may be reserved for Indium, until you have the Naquadah chain.
§aGallium§r, §aChrome§r, §aNiobium§r, §aRare Earths§r, §aGlowstone§r are §6Byproducts§r you want to prioritise (§oif I am missing any, hit us up on Discord and I may add it!§r).

§d-§r Storage Buses? As you may know, automating with AE2 is very powerful.
§3ME Storage Buses§r can route items effortlessly. They also have a huge whitelist or blacklist configuration. Put them on the §3TungstenSteel Crates§r, to buffer the items... or use a dedicated AE2 network, you choose.


More things to note:
The §aSmart Filter§r§r can be used for Electrolyzable items (refer back to the "200 IQ Quest" with the Smart Filter), but you may prefer setting up filter §emanually§r for that.
The §aSmart Filter§r can also be used to be configured to filter §dsiftable Purified Crushed Ores§r.
For ores that you want to process but don't want the Byproducts as it would take too long in the machines, prioritize filtering them for quick washing.
The typically "best" path is: Macerator -> Ore Washing -> Thermal Centrifuge -> Macerator. If you deviate from it for various reasons, you will have to set filters §emanually§r.

Perhaps you never noticed the §9"chance per tier"§r when hovering over the bonus outputs in §2JEI§r?
Each overclock above the required tier will add that bonus to the chanced output!

This means the §3EV Macerator§r yields §6more Byproducts§r!

You might ask: is it time to setup ore processing on large scale perhaps...? Nope!
Well... Running all the ores with a maceration step into this EV Macerator is fair.
But I would still recommend cherry-picking whatever ores you want byproducts of.

§oAll in one! This Quest describes the Tungsten Chain.§r

§aTungsten§r is obtained from either §eTungstate§r or §eScheelite§r, which are part of the same vein in the End.

Just like the §dRutile§r chain, you will only need to input one item type, and everything else will be looped perfectly!

§oAre you noticing a pattern? It's not just my imagination...§r

§oThe Ultimate Combustion fuel Generator!§r

To run the §3Extreme Combustion Engine§r, you will most likely want to boost it (§oelse why would you bother...§r).
You will want a §34A IV Dynamo Hatch§r as the output, and one §3Vacuum Freezer§r for §aLiquid Oxygen§r.

Don't forget to keep it supplied with a small amount of §aLubricant§r.

The §3ECE§r is also void-free, unlike Large Turbines. Any energy that cannot be output will momentarily pause the multiblock.


§bLore:§r The ECE comes from GT:NH. However... the story is not so great. The stats on the tooltip looked similar to this one, so far so good.
However if you made calculations, you ended up realizing you needed to run around 16 whole HV Vacuum Freezers to keep up with Liquid Oxygen...
The one and only fuel it would accept is High Octane Gasoline, which was stated to be burned at 300% efficiency when boosted, but it was a lie! The efficiency remained 100%!
The GT:NH team recently decided to rework the ECE among other power options, phew!

§oWho needs Stargate when you have Star Trek!§r

§aDuranium§r is a material from Star Trek, and is used for a few things in GT. It makes some pretty awesome pipes, but otherwise you won't need much of this quite yet.

§bLore§r: In some versions of GT5u, this material was entirely white. In fact, most fusion materials and later were like this. Boring!

§oPlasma? Turbine? What!? That's not even possible!
